<font color="#FF0000">KEEPING THE RECORD STRAIGHT</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 14 23:56:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook &amp; Nick,<br>
     Can we lay off the selective remembrance of history?  Yes, there were Communist sympathizers in the anti-war movement.  It would have been very unlikely for them not to be involved.  That doesn't mean everybody against the war was a Communist or fellow traveler.  You guys sound like the Joseph McCarthy who dominated my home state's politics in the '50s while I was growing up.  Not very pretty.  Let's see, does opposition to the war make Al Gore Sr., Fulbright,  Pete McCloskey, Gene McCarthy and Robert Kennedy all Communists or Communist sympathizers?  God is not a left wing radical, but neither is He conservative Republican..... speaking of which, the conservative Republicans referred to Vietnam as a &quot;Democrat war&quot; until most of the Democratic Party turned against it.  As for a danger of a Communist takeover; the only time there was ever a real worry was in the '30s.  The attempt to gain control over the labor movement in the late '40s was a dismal failure.  The '60s radicals got a lot of ink, but never had any real control on the levers of power.  They probably have more influence today through tenure in academia, although the current gospel is not Marxism, but moral relativism, political correctness and deconstruction of anything smacking of western culture.  Yet a backlash is already picking up steam.  Like Sinclair Lewis (&quot;It Can't Happen Here&quot;), I believe that if our democracy ever falls, the blows will come from the far right, not the left.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


